## 3.2 Retrieving data for TensorFlow/Keras models

TensorFlow provides several mechanisms to load datasets efficiently, depending
on dataset size and complexity.

---

### 3.2.1 tf.data API

The `tf.data` API is the most scalable option for building complex, high–
performance input pipelines. It supports parallel reading, caching, mapping,
batching, and prefetching.

#### Figure 3.7 — End-to-end tf.data pipeline
<p align="left"><img src="./figure/figure3.7.png" width="60%"></p>

---

### 3.2.2 Keras DataGenerators

DataGenerators read images from directories and apply real–time augmentation.
They are suitable when the full dataset does not fit into memory.

---

### 3.2.3 tensorflow-datasets (TFDS)

TFDS automatically downloads, prepares, validates, and splits common datasets.
It is the fastest way to load standardized benchmark datasets.

---

## Summary

Chapter 3 introduced the three Keras model–building APIs:
Sequential, Functional, and Sub-classing. It also presented three methods of
retrieving data in TensorFlow: the tf.data API, DataGenerators, and TFDS.
Together, these tools form a flexible and scalable ML development workflow.
